{'solution': "It is appropriate to thank your therapist in your MA thesis acknowledgments, but you should exercise caution. First, check with your therapist to ensure they are comfortable being acknowledged publicly. Consider their background in your field, as this might affect perceptions and professional boundaries. The acknowledgment should be brief, professional, and focus on their role as a sounding board and advisor without delving into personal or confidential details. Be mindful of potential ethical concerns and the impact on the therapeutic relationship. By respecting these guidelines, you can appropriately recognize your therapist's contributions while maintaining professional boundaries.", 'atomic': False, 'depth': 0, 'original_problem': [{'role': 'user', 'content': "Would it be appropriate to thank my therapist in my MA thesis acknowledgements? My therapist has a background in my field, before they switched to psychology, and has been an amazing sounding board for some of my ideas over the past couple years. They've genuinely helped me to recontextualize some ideas and open up new doors I hadn't considered before in my research, and given some great advice on how to keep my enthusiasm for my topic going. That's on top of the more typical stuff like helping me to manage my impostor syndrome and ADHD. Basically I wouldn't even be in grad school without them and I'd like to be able to thank them in my MA thesis' acknowledgements section (once I finish the damn thing... getting there). Just by name alongside friends and colleagues, not necessarily giving details on who they are.  I'm quite open about being in therapy and not concerned about people knowing, but more worried that it would be inappropriate in the therapist-patient relationship, or that it might have repercussions for me or them that I haven't forseen. Anyone have experience with this?"}], 'subproblems': ['Is it appropriate to thank a therapist in academic acknowledgements considering professional boundaries?', "How does the content of the thesis acknowledgements relate to the therapist's professional role and contributions?", 'What are the potential implications of publicly acknowledging a therapist in academic writing?', 'Is there a risk of breach of confidentiality or professional ethical guidelines when thanking a therapist in an acknowledgements section?'], 'sub_solutions': ["It is generally appropriate to thank a therapist in your MA thesis acknowledgments, but you should exercise caution. First, check with your therapist to ensure they are comfortable being acknowledged publicly. Consider their background in your field, as this might affect perceptions and professional boundaries. The acknowledgment should be brief, professional, and focus on their role as a sounding board and advisor without delving into personal or confidential details. Be mindful of potential ethical concerns and the impact on the therapeutic relationship. By respecting these guidelines, you can appropriately recognize your therapist's contributions while maintaining professional boundaries.", 'It is not appropriate to thank a therapist in the acknowledgements section of an MA thesis due to potential breaches of confidentiality, blurring of professional boundaries, and possible discomfort for both parties. This practice may also affect the perceived objectivity of the academic work and could be seen as unprofessional. Therefore, it is advisable to exclude thanking a therapist in this context and instead acknowledge support in a more general manner to maintain appropriate boundaries and ensure the focus remains on academic contributions.', 'It is academically appropriate to thank your therapist in your MA thesis acknowledgments by mentioning their name and expressing gratitude for their professional support. You should acknowledge their contributions in a general manner, avoiding specifics about personal therapy sessions, and ensure their consent is obtained. This approach respect